Mental Health America
· 9 hrs ·

Today’s #StressFreeSaturday challenge is about hobbies.

Hobbies allow us to relax and sort of “zone out” while doing something we find enjoyable. Hobbies can be physical like golf, gardening, or dancing, or they can be activities like writing, making music, crafting or cosplaying that provide an opportunity to flex our creative muscles. In addition to being great stress relievers, research shows that hobbies can have positive effects on overall wellbeing and activities like ...drawing, painting, and molding clay have been scientifically proven to help people who have been exposed to trauma.

Derek Hess is an artist American artist most well-known for his concert posters and politically charged art pieces. He is also responsible for the awesome “Fight in the Open” shirt design in the MHA Store . We talked to Derek about how art and creativity have impacted his recovery from mental health and substance use issues. Check out the interview here: http://bit.ly/2qXQGkC

What are your hobbies? How do you get creative? Show us how you get creative by posting with #4mind4body. #mhm2018

I grew up hearing horror stories, similar as depicted in "One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest"...As the ...years have passed, I have become one of the best counselors in NC, if not in the country. Yes, I will brag...In the eighties, I opened my own private practice, seeing thousands of people; became an EAP for Phillip Morris; helped open Charter Pines Hospital and our local psychiatric center...attended workshops all over the country; certifications. I have worked with the doctor to the street person; every walk of life...we have come a long way, but have a very long way to go, especially with the psychiatric shortage in our country..."The head is attached and controls the body"...my saying and belief.
